Paul:

I thought after I wrote the comment about being more fluent in reading 
QS that it might be disconcerting.  I read two of the articles in the 
News in QS with interest today, and I have been reading what others are 
writing by hand in QS without problems in recent weeks.  I write it 
fluently just as Moira mentioned she does.  The problem is not with QS 
but with the amount of practice that we receive.  I just cannot read QS 
as fast as TO, which is not surprising when you consider that we are 
surrounded by TO all the time and that we learned it as children. I 
daresay that if as a child you had been told how TO worked, but were 
given no reading practice in it, no one around you used it, and you 
never received anything written in it, you would be just as slow at 
reading TO as you are now at reading QS.

I would like to attain the reading speed in QS that I have in TO.  That 
goal is still some distance away, but it is getting closer.  For the 
first time, with the ability to communicate effectively in QS and to 
read articles, news, etc. written in it, I have no question that goal 
can be attained.  I can already see that my QS reading speed has been 
increasing in recent weeks.  And even now, I&#39;m not reading QS every day.

Just as a beginning TO reader sounds words out, we have to do that in QS 
until we begin to automatically recognize word outlines.  Until recently 
that has not been feasible because there are too few of us, and we tend 
to only read what we write ourselves.  For instance, I take notes in QS 
as secretary of a club I&#39;m in.  I then go back and transliterate them on 
the computer for the club records.  Thus, my reading speed isn&#39;t 
critical and QS is still useful. 

A fluent reader recognizes words at sight and doesn&#39;t have to break them 
down into individual syllables or letters.  However, in reading your 
news today, I saw numerous words in QS for the first time.  The shorter, 
common words I read quickly and essentially automatically just as I do 
in TO.  But three, four and five syllable words that are unfamiliar are 
a different matter.  Here are a few words I remember reading in QS for 
the first time today, and there are countless others: Islamabad, Islamic 
militants, Afghanistan, Land Cruiser, bullet-proofed (this last one 
hasn&#39;t come up much in my personal note-taking.)   :-).

Since the term &quot;Islamic militants&quot; was in the Pakistan story several 
times, it began looking familiar by the end of the story, but that is 
what has to occur to build up reading speed.


Paige

P.S.  Here is an example of the pressure we face against using QS.  A 
few years ago, I was taking notes in QS in a case.  Later my father, 
with whom I practiced, would be looking at a file, and tell me that I 
needed to write in TO.  His customary comment was, &quot;What if you get hit 
by a bus, and I have to take this case over.  I won&#39;t be able to read 
your notes.&quot;  The same problem exists when my secretary is working on a 
document and has to refer to the file.  If there are notes in QS, I have 
to rewrite them for her, which isn&#39;t exactly a time-saver.

What would be interesting would be for someone to teach their child to 
read QS before they go to school and see how easily they take to it.



